[0m[49m[39m  219, 227[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  220, 228[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  221, 229[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  222, 230[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  223, 231[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Location Service** | Road-network travel time calculations with real-time traffic |
[0m[49m[39m  224, 232[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Real-time dispatch scoring, GPS processing, hospital status updates |
[0m[49m[39m  225, 233[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Fleet state store (unit positions, statuses, capabilities) and hospital status |
[0m[49m[39m  226, 234[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon ElastiCache (Redis)** | Cached travel time matrices for low-latency dispatch lookups |
[0m[49m[39m  227, 235[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates background repositioning optimization workflow |
[0m[49m[39m  228, 236[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Hosts demand forecast model for coverage optimization |
[0m[49m[39m  229, 237[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams** | Ingests high-throughput GPS location stream from fleet |
[0m[49m[39m  230, 238[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Routes hospital status events and triggers scheduled repositioning |
[0m[49m[39m  231, 239[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | Exposes dispatch API to CAD system integration |
[0m[49m[39m  232, 240[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data stores |
[0m[49m[39m  233, 241[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Metrics, alarms, dashboards for response time monitoring |
[0m[49m[39m  234, 242[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  235, 243[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  236, 244[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  237, 245[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  238, 246[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  239, 247[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Ingest fleet GPS and maintain state.** Every ambulance reports its GPS position every 5 to 15 seconds. These positions flow through Kinesis into a Lambda processor that updates the fleet state table. The state table is the single source of truth for "where is every unit right now and what are they doing?" Without this real-time state, the dispatch optimizer is working with stale information, and stale information in EMS means sending a unit that's actually 15 minutes away instead of the one that's 3 minutes away. The state table also tracks unit status transitions: available, dispatched, en route, on scene, transporting, at hospital, returning. Each transition updates the record and potentially triggers a coverage recalculation.
[0m[49m[39m  240, 248[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  241, 249[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  242, 250[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION process_gps_update(gps_event):
[0m[49m[39m  243, 251[0m:[39m[49m     // GPS event contains: unit_id, latitude, longitude, timestamp, speed, heading
[0m[49m[39m  244, 252[0m:[39m[49m     unit_id   = gps_event.unit_id
[0m[49m[39m  245, 253[0m:[39m[49m     latitude  = gps_event.latitude
[0m[49m[39m  246, 254[0m:[39m[49m     longitude = gps_event.longitude
[0m[49m[39m  247, 255[0m:[39m[49m     timestamp = gps_event.timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  248, 256[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  249, 257[0m:[39m[49m     // Update the fleet state table with the new position.
[0m[49m[39m  250, 258[0m:[39m[49m     // Use a conditional write to avoid overwriting with an older GPS fix
[0m[49m[39m  251, 259[0m:[39m[49m     // (out-of-order delivery is possible with streaming systems).
[0m[49m[39m  252, 260[0m:[39m[49m     UPDATE fleet_state_table
[0m[49m[39m  253, 261[0m:[39m[49m         SET latitude      = latitude,
[0m[49m[39m  254, 262[0m:[39m[49m             longitude     = longitude,
[0m[49m[39m  255, 263[0m:[39m[49m             last_gps_time = timestamp,
[0m[49m[39m  256, 264[0m:[39m[49m             speed         = gps_event.speed,
[0m[49m[39m  257, 265[0m:[39m[49m             heading       = gps_event.heading
[0m[49m[39m  258, 266[0m:[39m[49m         WHERE unit_id = unit_id
[0m[49m[39m  259, 267[0m:[39m[49m         AND last_gps_time < timestamp   // only accept newer fixes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If conditional write fails (out-of-order fix), catch the exception and discard.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This is expected behavior, not an error. Log at DEBUG level for troubleshooting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Do NOT retry or raise; the newer fix is already in the table.
[0m[49m[39m  260, 271[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  261, 272[0m:[39m[49m     // If the unit is currently en route to a call, recalculate ETA.
[0m[49m[39m  262, 273[0m:[39m[49m     unit_record = GET fleet_state_table WHERE unit_id = unit_id
[0m[49m[39m  263, 274[0m:[39m[49m     IF unit_record.status == "EN_ROUTE":
[0m[49m[39m  264, 275[0m:[39m[49m         new_eta = calculate_travel_time(latitude, longitude, unit_record.destination)
[0m[49m[39m  265, 276[0m:[39m[49m         UPDATE fleet_state_table SET current_eta = new_eta WHERE unit_id = unit_id
[0m[49m[39m  266, 277[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  267, 278[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  268, 279[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Score candidate units for dispatch.** When a call comes in, the dispatch optimizer needs to evaluate every available unit that meets the capability requirement. For each candidate, it computes a composite score that balances response time (primary), coverage impact (secondary), and operational factors (crew fatigue, fuel level, time remaining on shift). The scoring function is the heart of the system. A pure "closest unit" approach is fast but myopic. The scoring function adds system-level awareness: "yes, Unit 3 is closest, but sending it leaves the entire north zone uncovered, and Unit 5 is only 90 seconds farther." This is where optimization beats human intuition at scale.
[0m[49m[39m  269, 280[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  270, 281[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  271, 282[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION score_candidates(call, available_units, fleet_state, coverage_model):
[0m[49m[39m  272, 283[0m:[39m[49m     // call contains: location (lat/lng), priority (1-5), required_capability (ALS/BLS),
[0m[49m[39m  273, 284[0m:[39m[49m     //               nature_code, patient_age
[0m[49m[39m  274, 285[0m:[39m[49m     candidates = []
[0m[49m[39m  275, 286[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  276, 287[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each unit in available_units:
[0m[49m[39m  277, 288[0m:[39m[49m         // Filter: unit must meet capability requirement
[0m[49m[39m  278, 289[0m:[39m[49m         IF call.required_capability == "ALS" AND unit.capability != "ALS":
[0m[49m[39m  279, 290[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE  // skip this unit, it can't handle this call
[0m[49m[39m  280, 291[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  281, 292[0m:[39m[49m         // Get travel time from unit's current position to call location.
[0m[49m[39m  282, 293[0m:[39m[49m         // Check cache first; fall back to routing service for cache miss.
[0m[49m[39m  283, 294[0m:[39m[49m         travel_time = get_travel_time(
[0m[49m[39m  284, 295[0m:[39m[49m             origin      = (unit.latitude, unit.longitude),
[0m[49m[39m  285, 296[0m:[39m[49m             destination = call.location
[0m[49m[39m  286, 297[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  287, 298[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  288, 299[0m:[39m[49m         // Calculate coverage impact: what happens to system coverage if we send this unit?
[0m[49m[39m  289, 300[0m:[39m[49m         // This is the key differentiator from simple proximity dispatch.
[0m[49m[39m  290, 301[0m:[39m[49m         coverage_impact = coverage_model.evaluate_removal(unit.unit_id, unit.zone)
[0m[49m[39m  291, 302[0m:[39m[49m         // coverage_impact is a score from 0 (no impact) to 1 (critical gap created)
[0m[49m[39m  292, 303[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  293, 304[0m:[39m[49m         // Operational factors
[0m[49m[39m  294, 305[0m:[39m[49m         hours_on_shift  = (current_time - unit.shift_start) / 3600
[0m[49m[39m  295, 306[0m:[39m[49m         fatigue_penalty = 0.0
[0m[49m[39m  296, 307[0m:[39m[49m         IF hours_on_shift > 10:
[0m[49m[39m  297, 308[0m:[39m[49m             fatigue_penalty = 0.1 * (hours_on_shift - 10)  // slight penalty for long shifts
[0m[49m[39m  298, 309[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  299, 310[0m:[39m[49m         // Composite score (lower is better)
[0m[49m[39m  300, 311[0m:[39m[49m         // Weights are configurable and should be tuned per system
[0m[49m[39m  301, 312[0m:[39m[49m         score = (
[0m[49m[39m  302, 313[0m:[39m[49m             0.60 * normalize(travel_time, max=20)     // response time (dominant factor)
[0m[49m[39m  303, 314[0m:[39m[49m           + 0.25 * coverage_impact                     // coverage preservation
[0m[49m[39m  304, 315[0m:[39m[49m           + 0.10 * fatigue_penalty                     // crew welfare
[0m[49m[39m  305, 316[0m:[39m[49m           + 0.05 * normalize(unit.calls_today, max=10) // workload balance
[0m[49m[39m  306, 317[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  307, 318[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  308, 319[0m:[39m[49m         // Priority 1 calls: override coverage concern, pure speed matters
[0m[49m[39m  309, 320[0m:[39m[49m         IF call.priority == 1:
[0m[49m[39m  310, 321[0m:[39m[49m             score = 0.90 * normalize(travel_time, max=20) + 0.10 * coverage_impact
[0m[49m[39m  311, 322[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  312, 323[0m:[39m[49m         candidates.append({
[0m[49m[39m  313, 324[0m:[39m[49m             unit_id:      unit.unit_id,
[0m[49m[39m  314, 325[0m:[39m[49m             travel_time:  travel_time,
[0m[49m[39m  315, 326[0m:[39m[49m             score:        score,
[0m[49m[39m  316, 327[0m:[39m[49m             coverage_gap: coverage_impact
[0m[49m[39m  317, 328[0m:[39m[49m         })
[0m[49m[39m  318, 329[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  319, 330[0m:[39m[49m     // Sort by score (ascending = best first)
[0m[49m[39m  320, 331[0m:[39m[49m     SORT candidates BY score ASC
[0m[49m[39m  321, 332[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN candidates
[0m[49m[39m  322, 333[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  323, 334[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  324, 335[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Select destination hospital.** Once a unit is assigned and the patient is assessed on scene, the system recommends a destination hospital. This is not always "the closest ED." A STEMI patient needs a cath lab. A stroke patient needs a certified stroke center. A trauma patient needs a Level I or II trauma center. And even when multiple hospitals meet the clinical requirement, you want to factor in current capacity: an ED with 40 patients boarding in the hallway and a 3-hour wait is not a good destination even if it's 2 minutes closer. Hospital diversion status, ED census, and specialty availability all feed into this decision.
[0m[49m[39m  325, 336[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  326, 337[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  327, 338[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION select_hospital(patient_needs, unit_location, hospital_status_table):
[0m[49m[39m  328, 339[0m:[39m[49m     // patient_needs contains: required_capabilities (list), acuity_level, special_requirements
[0m[49m[39m  329, 340[0m:[39m[49m     // Example: required_capabilities = ["cath_lab", "interventional_cardiology"]
[0m[49m[39m  330, 341[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  331, 342[0m:[39m[49m     eligible_hospitals = []
[0m[49m[39m  332, 343[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  333, 344[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each hospital in hospital_status_table:
[0m[49m[39m  334, 345[0m:[39m[49m         // Hard filter: hospital must have required capabilities
[0m[49m[39m  335, 346[0m:[39m[49m         IF NOT all(cap in hospital.capabilities FOR cap in patient_needs.required_capabilities):
[0m[49m[39m  336, 347[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[39m  337, 348[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  338, 349[0m:[39m[49m         // Hard filter: hospital must not be on diversion for this patient type
[0m[49m[39m  339, 350[0m:[39m[49m         IF hospital.diversion_status == "FULL_DIVERSION":
[0m[49m[39m  340, 351[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[39m  341, 352[0m:[39m[49m         IF hospital.diversion_status == "CONDITIONAL" AND patient_needs.acuity_level < 3:
[0m[49m[39m  342, 353[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE  // conditional diversion: only accepting critical patients
[0m[49m[39m  343, 354[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  344, 355[0m:[39m[49m         // Calculate transport time from unit's current location to hospital
[0m[49m[39m  345, 356[0m:[39m[49m         transport_time = get_travel_time(unit_location, hospital.location)
[0m[49m[39m  346, 357[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  347, 358[0m:[39m[49m         // Capacity score: lower ED census relative to capacity is better
[0m[49m[39m  348, 359[0m:[39m[49m         capacity_ratio = hospital.current_ed_census / hospital.ed_capacity
[0m[49m[39m  349, 360[0m:[39m[49m         capacity_score = capacity_ratio  // 0.0 = empty, 1.0 = at capacity
[0m[49m[39m  350, 361[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  351, 362[0m:[39m[49m         // Composite destination score (lower is better)
[0m[49m[39m  352, 363[0m:[39m[49m         dest_score = (
[0m[49m[39m  353, 364[0m:[39m[49m             0.50 * normalize(transport_time, max=30)  // transport time matters most
[0m[49m[39m  354, 365[0m:[39m[49m           + 0.35 * capacity_score                      // avoid overwhelmed EDs
[0m[49m[39m  355, 366[0m:[39m[49m           + 0.15 * (1.0 IF hospital.has_specialty_bed ELSE 0.5)  // specialty bed availability
[0m[49m[39m  356, 367[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  357, 368[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  358, 369[0m:[39m[49m         eligible_hospitals.append({
[0m[49m[39m  359, 370[0m:[39m[49m             hospital_id:    hospital.id,
[0m[49m[39m  360, 371[0m:[39m[49m             name:           hospital.name,
[0m[49m[39m  361, 372[0m:[39m[49m             transport_time: transport_time,
[0m[49m[39m  362, 373[0m:[39m[49m             score:          dest_score,
[0m[49m[39m  363, 374[0m:[39m[49m             capabilities:   hospital.capabilities
[0m[49m[39m  364, 375[0m:[39m[49m         })
[0m[49m[39m  365, 376[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  366, 377[0m:[39m[49m     SORT eligible_hospitals BY score ASC
[0m[49m[39m  367, 378[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN eligible_hospitals[0]  // recommend the best option
[0m[49m[39m  368, 379[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  369, 380[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  370, 381[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Background coverage optimization (repositioning).** This runs every 2 to 5 minutes, or whenever a significant state change occurs (unit dispatched, unit becomes available, demand spike detected). It solves the coverage problem: given current unit positions and predicted demand, are there zones where response time would exceed the target if a call came in? If so, which idle unit should reposition to close the gap? This is where the heavier optimization lives. Because it's not blocking an active emergency, it can take 10 to 30 seconds to solve. The solver formulates this as a set-covering problem: minimize the number of unit moves while ensuring every demand zone has at least one unit within the target response time.
[0m[49m[39m  371, 382[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  372, 383[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  373, 384[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION optimize_repositioning(fleet_state, demand_forecast, coverage_threshold):
[0m[49m[39m  374, 385[0m:[39m[49m     // Get all idle (available) units and their current positions
[0m[49m[39m  375, 386[0m:[39m[49m     idle_units = [u FOR u IN fleet_state WHERE u.status == "AVAILABLE"]
[0m[49m[39m  376, 387[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  377, 388[0m:[39m[49m     // Get demand zones with predicted call probability for next 30 minutes
[0m[49m[39m  378, 389[0m:[39m[49m     demand_zones = demand_forecast.get_zone_probabilities(horizon_minutes=30)
[0m[49m[39m  379, 390[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  380, 391[0m:[39m[49m     // For each demand zone, check if any idle unit can reach it within threshold
[0m[49m[39m  381, 392[0m:[39m[49m     uncovered_zones = []
[0m[49m[39m  382, 393[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each zone in demand_zones:
[0m[49m[39m  383, 394[0m:[39m[49m         IF zone.predicted_calls < 0.1:
[0m[49m[39m  384, 395[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE  // very low probability, don't worry about it
[0m[49m[39m  385, 396[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  386, 397[0m:[39m[49m         // Find the fastest unit that could reach this zone's centroid
[0m[49m[39m  387, 398[0m:[39m[49m         min_time = INFINITY
[0m[49m[39m  388, 399[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each unit in idle_units:
[0m[49m[39m  389, 400[0m:[39m[49m             time = get_travel_time(unit.location, zone.centroid)
[0m[49m[39m  390, 401[0m:[39m[49m             min_time = MIN(min_time, time)
[0m[49m[39m  391, 402[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  392, 403[0m:[39m[49m         IF min_time > coverage_threshold:
[0m[49m[39m  393, 404[0m:[39m[49m             uncovered_zones.append({
[0m[49m[39m  394, 405[0m:[39m[49m                 zone:           zone,
[0m[49m[39m  395, 406[0m:[39m[49m                 current_best:   min_time,
[0m[49m[39m  396, 407[0m:[39m[49m                 demand_weight:  zone.predicted_calls
[0m[49m[39m  397, 408[0m:[39m[49m             })
[0m[49m[39m  398, 409[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  399, 410[0m:[39m[49m     IF uncovered_zones is empty:
[0m[49m[39m  400, 411[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN []  // coverage is adequate, no moves needed
[0m[49m[39m  401, 412[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  402, 413[0m:[39m[49m     // Solve: which idle units should move where to cover the gaps?
[0m[49m[39m  403, 414[0m:[39m[49m     // Formulate as assignment problem: minimize total repositioning cost
[0m[49m[39m  404, 415[0m:[39m[49m     // while covering all high-priority gaps.
[0m[49m[39m  405, 416[0m:[39m[49m     moves = solve_coverage_assignment(
[0m[49m[39m  406, 417[0m:[39m[49m         units           = idle_units,
[0m[49m[39m  407, 418[0m:[39m[49m         gaps            = uncovered_zones,
[0m[49m[39m  408, 419[0m:[39m[49m         max_moves       = 3,              // don't move more than 3 units at once
[0m[49m[39m  409, 420[0m:[39m[49m         move_cost_weight = 0.3,           // penalize long repositioning drives
[0m[49m[39m  410, 421[0m:[39m[49m         coverage_weight  = 0.7            // prioritize closing coverage gaps
[0m[49m[39m  411, 422[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  412, 423[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  413, 424[0m:[39m[49m     // Issue move-up commands
[0m[49m[39m  414, 425[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each move in moves:
[0m[49m[39m  415, 426[0m:[39m[49m         SEND move_up_command(
[0m[49m[39m  416, 427[0m:[39m[49m             unit_id     = move.unit_id,
[0m[49m[39m  417, 428[0m:[39m[49m             destination = move.target_position,
[0m[49m[39m  418, 429[0m:[39m[49m             reason      = "Coverage gap in zone " + move.zone.id
[0m[49m[39m  419, 430[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  420, 431[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  421, 432[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN moves
[0m[49m[39m  422, 433[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  423, 434[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  424, 435[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Demand forecasting.** The repositioning optimizer needs to know where calls are likely to come from. This is a spatial-temporal forecasting problem. Historical call data shows strong patterns: more calls in residential areas during evenings, more in commercial districts during business hours, spikes near bars after midnight on weekends, seasonal patterns around holidays. The forecast model takes time-of-day, day-of-week, weather, and special events as inputs and produces a probability distribution over the service area grid. This doesn't need to be perfect. Even a rough forecast that captures the major patterns dramatically improves proactive positioning versus purely reactive dispatch.
[0m[49m[39m  425, 436[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  426, 437[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  427, 438[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION forecast_demand(current_time, weather, special_events, historical_data):
[0m[49m[39m  428, 439[0m:[39m[49m     // Divide service area into grid zones (typically 1km x 1km for urban, larger for rural)
[0m[49m[39m  429, 440[0m:[39m[49m     // For each zone, predict call probability in the next 30-minute window
[0m[49m[39m  430, 441[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  431, 442[0m:[39m[49m     features = {
[0m[49m[39m  432, 443[0m:[39m[49m         hour_of_day:    current_time.hour,
[0m[49m[39m  433, 444[0m:[39m[49m         day_of_week:    current_time.weekday,
[0m[49m[39m  434, 445[0m:[39m[49m         month:          current_time.month,
[0m[49m[39m  435, 446[0m:[39m[49m         is_holiday:     check_holiday_calendar(current_time),
[0m[49m[39m  436, 447[0m:[39m[49m         temperature:    weather.temperature,
[0m[49m[39m  437, 448[0m:[39m[49m         precipitation:  weather.precipitation_mm,
[0m[49m[39m  438, 449[0m:[39m[49m         special_events: encode_events(special_events)  // concerts, sports, etc.
[0m[49m[39m  439, 450[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  440, 451[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  441, 452[0m:[39m[49m     // Call the trained ML model (hosted on SageMaker endpoint)
[0m[49m[39m  442, 453[0m:[39m[49m     zone_predictions = invoke_sagemaker_endpoint(
[0m[49m[39m  443, 454[0m:[39m[49m         endpoint_name = "ems-demand-forecast",
[0m[49m[39m  444, 455[0m:[39m[49m         payload       = features
[0m[49m[39m  445, 456[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  446, 457[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  447, 458[0m:[39m[49m     // zone_predictions is a map: zone_id -> predicted_call_count (float, 0 to N)
[0m[49m[39m  448, 459[0m:[39m[49m     // Normalize to probabilities for the coverage optimizer
[0m[49m[39m  449, 460[0m:[39m[49m     total_predicted = SUM(zone_predictions.values())
[0m[49m[39m  450, 461[0m:[39m[49m     zone_probabilities = {
[0m[49m[39m  451, 462[0m:[39m[49m         zone_id: count / total_predicted
[0m[49m[39m  452, 463[0m:[39m[49m         FOR zone_id, count IN zone_predictions
[0m[49m[39m  453, 464[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  454, 465[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  455, 466[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN zone_probabilities
[0m[49m[39m  456, 467[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  457, 468[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  458, 469[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter14.08-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  459, 470[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  460, 471[0m:[39m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[39m  461, 472[0m:[39m[49m 
